.TH "Document.createEvent" "JS" "February 8, 2024" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Document.createEvent \- Document: createEvent() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] Many methods used with \f[CR]createEvent\f[R], such
as \f[CR]initCustomEvent\f[R], are deprecated.
Use event constructors instead.
.RE
.PP
Creates an event of the type specified.
The returned object should be first initialized and can then be passed
to \f[CR]EventTarget.dispatchEvent\f[R].
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
createEvent(type)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]type\f[R]
A string that represents the type of event to be created.
Possible event types include \f[CR]\[dq]UIEvents\[dq]\f[R],
\f[CR]\[dq]MouseEvents\[dq]\f[R], \f[CR]\[dq]MutationEvents\[dq]\f[R],
and \f[CR]\[dq]HTMLEvents\[dq]\f[R].
See Notes section for details.
.SS Return value
An Event object.
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Create the event.\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] event = document.createEvent(\[dq]Event\[dq]);

\f[I]// Define that the event name is \[aq]build\[aq].\f[R]
event.initEvent(\[dq]build\[dq], \f[B]true\f[R], \f[B]true\f[R]);

\f[I]// Listen for the event.\f[R]
elem.addEventListener(
  \[dq]build\[dq],
  (e) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    \f[I]// e.target matches elem\f[R]
  },
  \f[B]false\f[R],
);

\f[I]// Target can be any Element or other EventTarget.\f[R]
elem.dispatchEvent(event);
.EE
.SH NOTES
Event type strings suitable for passing to \f[CR]createEvent()\f[R] are
listed in the \c
.UR https://dom.spec.whatwg.org/#dom-document-createevent
DOM standard \[em] see the table in step 2
.UE \c
\&.
Bear in mind that most event objects now have constructors, which are
the modern recommended way to create event object instances.
